t-size:10pt">We have concerns regarding the scope of any reform. Since the implementation of the April and July reforms, we have seen quite marked changes in tactics and approach by certain claimant law firms. In order to recover lost revenue as a result of the reducti</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">on in the fixed fee, additional medical reports being obtained for simple, modest whiplash claims is rapidly becoming commonplace. These reports are predominantly produced by psychologists and/or rehabilitation providers. The reports add little to the clai</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">m in terms of insight - the rehabilitation is often no more than a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">DVD</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> posted to the claimant or some telephone</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">based advice. The psychologist input </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">tend to mention issues such as</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> travel anxiety</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> flashbacks which settle in a matter of days or weeks. The</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">se additional reports combined can add up to £1600 in </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">extra</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">costs and are often obtained </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> the law firm</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s own medical agency. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We would add that</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">occasionally</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> these very early medical interventions appear contrary to NICE guidelines and to the detriment</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> of the claimant. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">This is simply a manipulation of the process to recover revenue. The Government must move via C</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">laims </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">rocess </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">eform</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> or process change to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">tackle this</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> before it becomes the norm. This obviously negates the overall ambition to reduce premium</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.62pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Given the above, we would like to understand how the Government will deliver truly independent and accredited medical evidence. The Legal Services Act allows A</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">lternative </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">usiness </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">tructures</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> whilst LASPO bans referral fees. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Zurich welcomes the wish of t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he Government to dismantle relationships between law firms and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> their </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">owned medical agencies. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">However, w</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e see competing legislation/strategy here and would like more detail on how </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Government plan</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> to square this particular circle.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.62pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The medical expert mu</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">st be given detail of the mechanics of the accident. This has to be a fundamental part of the process. This could be incorporated into a standard template report where the expert provides opinion as to the stated injury against the accident circumstances. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Experts have previously confirmed whiplash symptoms </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">even in a situation where</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> a simple clash of wing mirrors had taken place.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">There needs to be greater awareness and sharing of facts. </span><span style="fon