ana; font-size:10pt">We welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">TSC</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">’s insistence that the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> fully articulate their position on this very important point. Historically, the insur</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ance industry has been criticised for not doing enough to combat fraud (unfairly in our view) but now we find the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> reticent to deliver key change to support the fight against insurance fraud.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.62pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The Law Commission ha</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> recently sought views on whether </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">hould re-visit this key issue. Sixteen out of eighteen respondents confirmed that </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">should. The now </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">well-known</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> case of Summers &amp; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Fairclough</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> Homes </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">that Zurich took to the Supreme </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">C</span><span style="font-fa