/span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> say, 12 months. This would th</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">en stop “farming” of aged books of potential claims - from our experience a frequent source of fraudulent claims.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.62pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We are aware of one claimant law firm wh</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ich is</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> regularly presenting “new” claims where the period back to the actual accident date is often in excess of 600 days. This is clear evidence of farming and of individuals being coaxed into presenting claims. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Given the current state of knowledge surrounding </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">RTA compensation</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> we do not believe that limitation should be any more than 12 months. The Act retains Judicial discretion and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, therefore</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">safeguards</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> exist for the protection of innocent victims who may not be aware of their rights immediately.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Small </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Claims Track</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.62pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Whilst we welcomed the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">TSC</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">’s narrative that there were strong arguments for increasing the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">SCT</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, we were disappointed that </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the Committee </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">could not then support change. We would be interested to learn from the Committee what safeguards would n</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">eed to be in place to support an increase to £5000?</span><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.62pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">LASPO introduced Damages Based Agreements for personal injury claims. If the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">SCT</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> were increased to £5000</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> then this is how many claimants would fund their claims. This is</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> in practice</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> no </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">differen</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to what is happening now, with most claimants ceding 25% of their damages to their lawyer under a CFA. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">To protect claimants further should the SCT be increased in the future, we would strongly advocate for a predictable damages tool (supported by </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Lord Just</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ice </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Jackson) to offer further consumer protection and transparency.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.62pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Finally, as a further safeguard to protect consumers with an increased </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">SCT</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, we would urge all stakeholders to re-consider </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Lord Justice</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">’s suggestion that a predictable damages tool be int</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">roduced for </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">lower value</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> claims. This would make the process more transparent and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">understandable for claimants and reduce timeframes to deliver settlement damages.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Conclusions</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">TSC</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">’s continued engagement and scrutiny in this important polic</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">y area.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We have articulated our concerns and would welcome the chance to discuss these further with members of the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">TSC</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. We would also express an over-arching </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">concern in terms of timeframes. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> ha</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> stated tha</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">t they </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">intend to work </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">at pace</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> - a comment which we welcome, but would like to see more structure and detail in the proposed changes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>